            "@type": "dctypes:Text",
            "chars": "<p id=\"docs-internal-guid-3a12698a-7fff-4bc0-91d9-1a29e50bd49d\" dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><em><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">HT.I.L2</span></em></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><strong><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial, sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Mr Gradgrind. Facts and figures [...]<br /><br /></span></strong></p>\n<p dir=\"ltr\" style=\"line-height: 1.38; margin-top: 0pt; margin-bottom: 0pt;\"><span style=\"font-size: 11pt; font-family: Arial,sans-serif; color: #000000; background-color: transparent; font-weight: 400; font-style: normal; font-variant: normal; text-decoration: none; vertical-align: baseline; white-space: pre-wrap;\">Dickens appears to have conceived Gradgrind&rsquo;s proclamation in his initial planning of the novel&rsquo;s opening chapters, and then transferred this phrase to the right-hand side of the Working Note as the sole memorandum for chapter 1. The opening lines in the published text are slightly different: &ldquo;Now, what I want is, Facts. Teach these boys and girls nothing but Facts. Facts alone are wanted in life&rdquo; (HT 47). Although these lines&ndash;and, indeed, the entirety of the novel&rsquo;s short opening chapter&ndash;are heavily revised in the manuscript, the word &ldquo;children&rdquo; never appears in Dickens&rsquo;s various formulations of the novel&rsquo;s opening sentences, as he moves between &ldquo;teach them&rdquo; and &ldquo;teach these young people&rdquo; before settling on &ldquo;teach these boys and girls.&rdquo;</span></p>\n<p>&nbsp;</p>",
